visible corneal ulcer on gross inspection of the eye. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluorescein instillation","Gonioscopy","Topical chloramphenicol","Saline eye lavage","Oral doxycycline"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of a corneal abrasion in the context of contact lens use. The most appropriate next step in management is \u003Cstrong\u003Efluorescein instillation\u003C/strong\u003E. Fluorescein dye is essential to highlight potential areas of corneal abrasion that may not be visible to the naked eye. This step is crucial for accurate diagnosis and guides further management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical chloramphenicol\u003C/strong\u003E is an antibiotic eye drop that may be appropriate for treating bacterial conjunctivitis or as prophylaxis after corneal abrasion is confirmed. However, it should not be administered before a thorough examination and diagnosis have been made.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGonioscopy\u003C/strong\u003E involves the use of a special lens (goniolens) to view the iridocorneal angle. It is typically used in cases of suspected acute angle-closure glaucoma or to assess the drainage angle of the eye. Given this patient\u0027s symptoms and presentation, gonioscopy is not indicated as the next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESaline eye lavage\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used to irrigate the eye following chemical exposure or to remove foreign bodies. In this case, there is no history of chemical exposure, and lavage is not the most appropriate next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used in ophthalmology for conditions such as meibomian gland dysfunction or recurrent corneal erosion syndrome. However, it is not indicated as an immediate management step for the presenting symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that contact lens use is a significant risk factor for bacterial keratitis, which can present similarly to a corneal abrasion. This underscores the importance of a thorough examination, including fluorescein staining, before initiating any treatment. After fluorescein staining, if a corneal abrasion is confirmed, management may include topical antibiotics, cycloplegics for comfort, and temporary discontinuation of contact lens use. If bacterial keratitis is suspected, urgent ophthalmology referral is necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fluorescein dye is required to highlight areas of corneal abrasion.","Contact lens use is a significant risk factor for bacterial keratitis.","A thorough clinical examination, including fluorescein staining, is essential before initiating treatment for suspected corneal abrasions."],"references":["Bowling B. Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). 2015. W B Saunders Salmon, J. F. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Wipperman JL, Dorsch JN. Evaluation and Management of Corneal Abrasions. Am Fam Physician. 2013;87(2):114-120. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2013/0115/p114.html","Arbabi EM, Kelly RJ, Carrim ZI. Corneal ulcers in general practice. Br J Gen Pract. 2018 Jan;68(666):49-50. doi: 10.3399/bjgp17X694385. PMID: 29284643; PMCID: PMC5737312."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96502"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"524"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96502"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T09:20:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T09:21:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"524"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114501"}}},"m